   404→                           Asked by Erdős and Gyárfás, who proved that this is the case when $G$ has maximum degree $\ll \log n/\log\log n$. A construction of Simonovits shows that this conjecture is false if we just have maximum degree $\leq Cn^{1/2}$, for some large enough $C$.<br><br>In <a href="https://web.math.princeton.edu/~nalon/PDFS/remark1901.pdf" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">this note</a> Alon solves this problem in a strong form, in particular proving that a triangle-free graph on $n$ vertices with maximum degree $&lt;n^{1/2-\epsilon}$ can be made into a triangle-free graph with diameter $2$ by adding at most $O(n^{2-\epsilon})$ edges.<br><br>See also <a href="/618" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[618]</a>.
